One model you could have is that US Treasury bills and US regional banks co=
mpete for savers=E2=80=99 money. If you want to put your cash somewhere saf=
e for a short term, you put it in the bank or you buy Treasury bills. In th=
e last few months, Treasury bills were offering much higher interest rates=
=C2=A0and=C2=A0looked much safer than a lot of regional bank accounts. This=
 was bad for the banks: People took their money out of the banks and put it=
 into Treasuries, the banks lost their cheap funding, their business got wo=
rse and a few of them failed.
But now there is the debt ceiling, and one consequence of that is that Trea=
sury bills, while they are   paying like 7%, no longer look all that safe. =
Which makes bank accounts=C2=A0relatively more attractive, even if they pay=
 less.=C2=A0Last week Bloomberg=E2=80=99s   Alice Atkins reported:

Trillions of dollars stowed away in short-term US Treasuries are looking an=
ything but safe as the debt ceiling deadline edges closer. That=E2=80=99s p=
rompted an ETF giant to warn that one of the year=E2=80=99s hottest haven t=
rades could be about to unwind =E2=80=94 and throw beleaguered regional ban=
ks a lifeline.
Lori Heinel, who oversees the biggest short-term US Treasury ETF as chief-i=
nvestment officer at State Street Global Advisors, a $3.6 trillion asset ma=
nager, is avoiding short-dated US debt in State Street=E2=80=99s actively-m=
anaged funds as a showdown in Washington over raising the US government=E2=
=80=99s $31.4 trillion borrowing limit enters its final days. =E2=80=A6
=E2=80=9CIf they really do press this to a point where there is a technical=
 default or some other extraordinary intervention, perversely it could crea=
te a huge flight of money back into bank deposits,=E2=80=9D Heinel said in =
an interview. =E2=80=9CBanks could be the most immediate beneficiary as peo=
ple look for alternatives to Treasury funds.=E2=80=9D

I don=E2=80=99t know, but I do think it would be very funny if a lot of peo=
ple were like =E2=80=9Cugh I can't trust the government anymore, guess it=
=E2=80=99s PacWest for me.=E2=80=9D But the Wall Street Journal reports tod=
ay that, if the debt ceiling=C2=A0is=C2=A0lifted, it=C2=A0will be bad for t=
he banks again:

Even once the debt ceiling is resolved, there may be more plot twists for A=
merican companies=E2=80=94especially deposit-hungry banks.
