</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The theory is pretty straightforward:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Banks are <a href=3D"https://link.mai=
l.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31597233.273415/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnL=
mNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTcvYmlnLWJhbmtzLXRydXN0LWZpcnN0LXJl=
cHVibGljLXdpdGgtdGhlaXItbW9uZXk_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUyNTIzX01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21=
lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjMwNTI1JnV0bV9jYW=
1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB07cf9bbd" itemprop=3D"Story=
Link" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> a confid=
ence business</a>. If people trust that a bank is safe and sound, they will=
 keep their money there; if they don=E2=80=99t, they won=E2=80=99t.</li>=09=
<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If people all pull their money out of a b=
ank, it <em>won=E2=80=99t </em>be safe and sound: It will have to sell off =
long-term assets to pay back depositors, it will get a bad price, and it wo=
n=E2=80=99t have enough to pay them all.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D=
"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-=
block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">So confidence in banks is self-fu=
lfilling, as is a lack of confidence.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5p=
x;">The most high-profile public indication of confidence in a publicly tra=
ded company is its stock price.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If=
 the stock price goes down, people will think that a company is in trouble.=
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">For most companies, this doesn=E2=
=80=99t matter that much: If it is <em>not </em>in trouble, it can ignore i=
ts stock price and just do its business and eventually the stock will sort =
itself out.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But for banks, it does=
 matter: If it <em>looks like </em>a bank is in trouble, people will pull t=
heir money out, and it <em>will </em>be in trouble.</li>=09<li style=3D"mar=
gin-bottom: 5px;">If it gets in enough trouble, its stock will go to zero.<=
/li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Retail investors posting on messag=
e boards can gang up with their friends and move stock prices.</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If they bet against a bank=E2=80=99s stock, an=
d then gang up with their friends to move that bank=E2=80=99s stock down, t=
hen they can destroy the bank and make a lot of money.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Is this theory right? Well. I mean, much of it=
 is kind of right, but you could object to bits of it. <em>Does </em>a fall=
ing stock price undermine confidence in a bank? Sometimes, probably, but th=
e point of bank deposits is that they are <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloo=
mbergbusiness.com/click/31597233.273415/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9=
vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDUtMDUvYmFuay1zdG9ja3MtbG9vay13b3JzZS10aGFuLW=
JhbmtzLWRvP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MjUyM19NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX=
3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIzMDUyNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVm=
Zg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB696df206" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"i=
temscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none =
!important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-=
bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> supposed to be information i=
nsensitive</a>, and it is possible that a lot of depositors in sleepy US re=
gional banks are <em>not </em>constantly checking Robinhood to see how thei=
r bank=E2=80=99s stock is doing. <em>Can </em>retail investors on message b=
oards gang up to move stock prices? That seems to be=C2=A0the lesson of the=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31597233.273415/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDItMjYvcmVk=
ZGl0LXBvc3RlcnMtcGljay10aGUtc3RvY2tzLW5vdz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTI1MjNfTU9ORVlTVFV=
GRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA1Mj=
UmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf02c6fc6" itempr=
op=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: =
#000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border=
-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;=
"> 2020 meme-stock mania</a>, but that might have been a very specific mome=
nt =E2=80=94 Covid lockdowns, bored traders, novelty =E2=80=94 that can=E2=
=80=99t be repeated arbitrarily.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Ultimately though this is not a very interesti=
ng theoretical question; it is an empirical question. If Reddit retail day =
traders bring down a bank, then we=E2=80=99ll know that Reddit retail day t=
raders can bring down a bank. If they don=E2=80=99t, then we won=E2=80=99t.=
<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: trans=
parent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Have they? I mean, I think the answer is no. S=
ome US regional banks have failed recently, but not, as far as I now, after=
 being particularly targeted by retail traders on social media. Credit Suis=
se Group AG <em>was </em>kind of targeted by retail traders on social media=
 last year =E2=80=94 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/31597233.273415/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVz=
LzIwMjItMTAtMTgvbWF0dC1sZXZpbmUtcy1tb25leS1zdHVmZi1jcmVkaXQtc3Vpc3NlLXdhcy1=
hLXJldmVyc2UtbWVtZS1zdG9jaz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTI1MjNfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaX=
VtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMzA1MjUmdXRtX2NhbXBha=
WduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1074d600" itemprop=3D"StoryLink=
" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">we talked abo=
ut it</a>; I called it a =E2=80=9Creverse meme stock=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 and=
 then <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31597233.273=
415/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMjA=
vdWJzLWdvdC1jcmVkaXQtc3Vpc3NlLWZvci1hbG1vc3Qtbm90aGluZz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTI1Mj=
NfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fd=
GVybT0yMzA1MjUmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd4a=
d8135" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;"> it <em>did </em>fail this March</a> due to deposit flight, =
but it does not seem like the deposit flight was caused by=C2=A0the social-=
media posting.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the experiment is ongoing. Gunjan Banerji =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/31597233.273415/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9wYWN3ZXN0LWJhbmstc3RvY2tzLW1lbWUtc3RvY=
2tzLTZjMDQyNDgyP21vZD1ocF9sZWFkX3Bvczk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd0d65dc9" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;"> reports at the Wall Street Journal</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A near-record number of shares in regional ban=
ks has changed hands this month, and the number of options bets against the=
 sector has exploded. Big Wall Street institutions and at-home individual i=
nvestors alike are taking part, feeding on each other=E2=80=99s selling and=
 buying.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Rookie traders are flooding social media with =
doomsday theories on the next bank that might fail. Others are loading up o=
n bank stocks, speculating that there will soon be an epic jump in shares.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The result? A market that moves from calm to c=
haotic faster than ever. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Before March, individual investors didn=E2=80=
=99t pay much attention to regional banks. Compared with GameStop, AMC or T=
esla, they were way too boring.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Stock gyrations can be punishing for any compa=
ny, but they can be fatal for banks, where confidence is currency. Although=
 a plunging share price shouldn=E2=80=99t have any immediate effect on a ba=
nk=E2=80=99s ability to satisfy its financial obligations, it can drive dep=
ositors to withdraw their money, which does.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CYou can create real panic,=E2=80=9D s=
aid Cem Karsan, founder of Chicago-based investment firm Kai Volatility Adv=
isors.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The article features =E2=80=9CDaniel Betancour=
t, a 30-year-old pub owner in Pomona, Calif.,=E2=80=9D who buys puts on ban=
k stocks and talks about it on Discord, and who scored a big win on PacWest=
 Bancorp earlier this month:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CI came to kill the banks,=E2=80=9D Be=
tancourt said in an investing chat room that he hosts on Discord. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">PacWest shares plummeted when markets opened, =
and he spotted his chance.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Put options trading in PacWest shares=E2=80=94=
the kinds of trades that would profit if the shares kept dropping=E2=80=94j=
umped to the highest level on record, according to Cboe Global Markets data=
 since 2008. =E2=80=A6 The contracts Betancourt had bought were now worth a=
round four times as much as he had paid for them, he said. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In his Discord chat room, traders celebrated, =
exchanging screenshots of winning trades or memes of Leonardo DiCaprio from=
 =E2=80=9CThe Wolf of Wall Street=E2=80=9D and Steve Carell from =E2=80=9CT=
he Big Short.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Betancourt got to work again. =E2=80=9CJust lo=
oking for another bank to go to zero,=E2=80=9D he said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">PacWest depositors were unnerved. The bank lat=
er disclosed that customers yanked nearly 10% of deposits during the week, =
mostly on May 4 and 5.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Did they withdraw their money because of his p=
osts on Discord? Because his put buying drove the stock down? Probably not.=
 And this did not drive PacWest into failure or anything.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still! Part of me, as an enjoyer of weird fina=
ncial stuff, would be very interested to see a case of online retail trader=
s causing a bank failure. It does feel like it would be a <em>bad </em>thin=
g, though? Also, once you prove it can be done, why stop with one bank?</p>
